  "description": "Sinai billiards are a fascinating class of dynamical systems: in fact, despite their simple definition in terms of a dynamical billiard on a table given by a square or a two torus with a certain number of dispersing obstacles, they present some &#8220;nasty&#8221; features (related to the existence of &#8220;grazing&#8221; collisions) placing them slightly beyond the standard theory [&#8230;]",
  "content:encoded": "<p><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dynamical_billiards#Lorentz_gas,_aka_Sinai_billiard\">Sinai billiards</a> are a fascinating class of dynamical systems: in fact, despite their simple definition in terms of a <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dynamical_billiards\">dynamical billiard</a> on a table given by a square or a two torus with a certain number of dispersing obstacles, they present some &#8220;nasty&#8221; features (related to the existence of &#8220;grazing&#8221; collisions) placing them slightly beyond the standard theory of <a href=\"http://www.scholarpedia.org/article/Hyperbolic_dynamics\">smooth uniformly hyperbolic systems</a>.</p><p>The seminal works by several authors (including <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=1138952\">Sinai, Bunimovich, Chernov</a>, &#8230;) paved the way to establish many properties of Sinai billiards including the so-called <a href=\"http://www.scholarpedia.org/article/Decay_of_correlations\">fast decay of correlations</a> for the Liouville measure <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmu_%7B%5Ctext%7BSRB%7D%7D%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{&#92;mu_{&#92;text{SRB}}}\" class=\"latex\" /> (a feature which is illustrated in this numerical simulation [due to Dyatlov] <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aTMKmav0GBw\">here</a>).</p><p>Nevertheless, some ergodic-theoretical aspects of (certain) Sinai billiards were elucidated only very recently: for instance, the existence of an unique probability measure of maximal entropy <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmu_%7B%5Ctext%7Bmax%7D%7D%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{&#92;mu_{&#92;text{max}}}\" class=\"latex\" /> was proved by Baladi&#8211;Demers in this article <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=4073865\">here</a>.</p><p>An interesting remark made by Baladi&#8211;Demers is the fact that the maximal entropy measure <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmu_%7B%5Ctext%7Bmax%7D%7D%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{&#92;mu_{&#92;text{max}}}\" class=\"latex\" /> should be typically different from the Liouville measure <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmu_%7B%5Ctext%7BSRB%7D%7D%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{&#92;mu_{&#92;text{SRB}}}\" class=\"latex\" />: in fact, <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmu_%7B%5Ctext%7Bmax%7D%7D%3D%5Cmu_%7B%5Ctext%7BSRB%7D%7D%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{&#92;mu_{&#92;text{max}}=&#92;mu_{&#92;text{SRB}}}\" class=\"latex\" /> forces a <em>rigidity</em> property for periodic orbits, namely, the Lyapunov exponents of <em>all</em> periodic orbits coincide (note that this is a huge number of conditions because the number of periodic orbits of period <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cleq+n%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{&#92;leq n}\" class=\"latex\" /> grows exponentially with <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bn%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{n}\" class=\"latex\" />) and, in particular, there are no known examples of Sinai billiards where <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmu_%7B%5Ctext%7Bmax%7D%7D%3D%5Cmu_%7B%5Ctext%7BSRB%7D%7D%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{&#92;mu_{&#92;text{max}}=&#92;mu_{&#92;text{SRB}}}\" class=\"latex\" />.</p><p>In a recent paper, <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2003.09345\">De Simoi&#8211;Leguil&#8211;Vinhage&#8211;Yang</a> showed that <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmu_%7B%5Ctext%7Bmax%7D%7D%3D%5Cmu_%7B%5Ctext%7BSRB%7D%7D%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{&#92;mu_{&#92;text{max}}=&#92;mu_{&#92;text{SRB}}}\" class=\"latex\" /> forces another rigidity property for periodic orbits, namely, the <a href=\"https://www.encyclopediaofmath.org/index.php/Birkhoff_normal_form\">Birkhoff normal forms</a> (see also <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=1326374\">Section 6 of Chapter 6 of Hasselblatt&#8211;Katok book</a> and <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=2583264\">Appendix A of Moreira&#8211;Yoccoz article</a>) at periodic orbits whose invariant manifolds produce <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Homoclinic_orbit\">homoclinic orbits</a> are all <em>linear</em>. In particular, they proposed in Remark 5.6 of their preprint to prove that <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmu_%7B%5Ctext%7Bmax%7D%7D%5Cneq%5Cmu_%7B%5Ctext%7BSRB%7D%7D%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{&#92;mu_{&#92;text{max}}&#92;neq&#92;mu_{&#92;text{SRB}}}\" class=\"latex\" /> for certain Sinai billiards by computing the Taylor expansion of the derivative of the billiard map at a periodic orbit of period two and checking that its quadratic part is non-degenerate.</p><p>In this short post, we explain that the strategy from the previous paragraph can be implemented to verify the non-linearity of the Birkhoff normal form at a periodic orbit of period two of the Sinai billiards in triangular lattices considered by Baladi&#8211;Demers.</p><blockquote><b>Remark 1</b> <em>In our subsequent discussion, we shall assume some familiarity with the basic aspects of billiards maps described in the classical <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=2229799\">book of Chernov&#8211;Markarian</a>.</em></blockquote><p>&nbsp;</p><p><b>1. Sinai billiards in triangular lattices</b></p><p>We consider the Sinai billiard table on the hexagonal torus obtained from the following picture (extracted from Baladi&#8211;Demers article):</p><p><a href=\"https://matheuscmss.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/sinai-j-lattice.png\"><img loading=\"lazy\" data-attachment-id=\"3839\" data-permalink=\"https://matheuscmss.wordpress.com/2020/04/16/maximal-entropy-measures-and-birkhoff-normal-forms-of-certain-sinai-billiards/sinai-j-lattice/\" data-orig-file=\"https://matheuscmss.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/sinai-j-lattice.png\" data-orig-size=\"400,286\" data-comments-opened=\"1\" data-image-meta=\"{\"aperture\":\"0\",\"credit\":\"\",\"camera\":\"\",\"caption\":\"\",\"created_timestamp\":\"0\",\"copyright\":\"\",\"focal_length\":\"0\",\"iso\":\"0\",\"shutter_speed\":\"0\",\"title\":\"\",\"orientation\":\"0\"}\" data-image-title=\"sinai-j-lattice\" data-image-description=\"\" data-image-caption=\"\" data-medium-file=\"https://matheuscmss.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/sinai-j-lattice.png?w=300\" data-large-file=\"https://matheuscmss.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/sinai-j-lattice.png?w=400\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-3839\" src=\"https://matheuscmss.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/sinai-j-lattice.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"400\" height=\"286\" srcset=\"https://matheuscmss.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/sinai-j-lattice.png 400w, https://matheuscmss.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/sinai-j-lattice.png?w=150&h=107 150w, https://matheuscmss.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/sinai-j-lattice.png?w=300&h=215 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 400px) 100vw, 400px\" /></a></p><p>Here, the obstacles are disks of radii <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{1}\" class=\"latex\" /> centered at the points of a triangular lattice and the distance between adjacent scatterers is <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bd%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{d}\" class=\"latex\" />.</p><p>As it is discussed in Baladi&#8211;Demers paper, the billiard map <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BF%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{F}\" class=\"latex\" /> has a probability measure of maximal entropy whenever <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B2%3Cd%3C4%2F%5Csqrt%7B3%7D%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{2<d<4/&#92;sqrt{3}}\" class=\"latex\" /> (where the limit case <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bd%3D2%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{d=2}\" class=\"latex\" /> corresponds to touching obstacles and the limit case <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bd%3D4%2F%5Csqrt%7B3%7D%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{d=4/&#92;sqrt{3}}\" class=\"latex\" /> produces &#8220;infinite horizon&#8221;).</p><p><b>2. Billiard map near a periodic orbit of period two</b></p><p>We want to study the billiard map <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BF%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{F}\" class=\"latex\" /> near the periodic orbit of period two given by the horizontal segment between <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bp_0%3D%281%2C0%29%5Cin%5Cmathbb%7BR%7D%5E2%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{p_0=(1,0)&#92;in&#92;mathbb{R}^2}\" class=\"latex\" /> and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bp_1%3D%28d-1%2C0%29%5Cin%5Cmathbb%7BR%7D%5E2%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{p_1=(d-1,0)&#92;in&#92;mathbb{R}^2}\" class=\"latex\" />.</p><p>A trajectory leaving the point <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Be%5E%7Bi%5Ctheta%7D%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{e^{i&#92;theta}}\" class=\"latex\" /> in the direction <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Be%5E%7Bi%5Cpsi%7D%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{e^{i&#92;psi}}\" class=\"latex\" /> travels along the line <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Be%5E%7Bi%5Ctheta%7D%2Bse%5E%7Bi%5Cpsi%7D%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{e^{i&#92;theta}+se^{i&#92;psi}}\" class=\"latex\" /> until it hits the boundary of the disk of radius <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{1}\" class=\"latex\" /> and center <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%28d-1%2C0%29%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{(d-1,0)}\" class=\"latex\" /> for the first time <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bt%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{t}\" class=\"latex\" />. By definition, the time <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bt%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{t}\" class=\"latex\" /> is the smallest solution of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7Ce%5E%7Bi%5Ctheta%7D%2Bse%5E%7Bi%5Cpsi%7D-d%7C%3D1%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{|e^{i&#92;theta}+se^{i&#92;psi}-d|=1}\" class=\"latex\" />, i.e.,</p><p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+s%5E2%2B2%28%5Ccos%28%5Cpsi-%5Ctheta%29-d%5Ccos%5Cpsi%29s%2B%28d%5E2-2d%5Ccos%5Ctheta%29%3D0.&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"&#92;displaystyle s^2+2(&#92;cos(&#92;psi-&#92;theta)-d&#92;cos&#92;psi)s+(d^2-2d&#92;cos&#92;theta)=0.\" class=\"latex\" /></p><p>Hence, <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bt%3DB%28%5Ctheta%2C%5Cpsi%29-%5Csqrt%7BB%28%5Ctheta%2C%5Cpsi%29%5E2-A%28%5Ctheta%2C%5Cpsi%29%7D%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{t=B(&#92;theta,&#92;psi)-&#92;sqrt{B(&#92;theta,&#92;psi)^2-A(&#92;theta,&#92;psi)}}\" class=\"latex\" /> where <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BB%28%5Ctheta%2C%5Cpsi%29%3A%3Dd%5Ccos%5Cpsi-%5Ccos%28%5Cpsi-%5Ctheta%29%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{B(&#92;theta,&#92;psi):=d&#92;cos&#92;psi-&#92;cos(&#92;psi-&#92;theta)}\" class=\"latex\" /> and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BA%28%5Ctheta%2C%5Cpsi%29%3A%3Dd%5E2-2d%5Ccos%5Ctheta%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{A(&#92;theta,&#92;psi):=d^2-2d&#92;cos&#92;theta}\" class=\"latex\" />, the billiard trajectory starting at <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Be%5E%7Bi%5Ctheta%7D%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{e^{i&#92;theta}}\" class=\"latex\" /> in the direction <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Be%5E%7Bi%5Cpsi%7D%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{e^{i&#92;psi}}\" class=\"latex\" /> hits the obstacle at</p><p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+e%5E%7Bi%5Ctheta%7D%2B%28B%28%5Ctheta%2C%5Cpsi%29-%5Csqrt%7BB%28%5Ctheta%2C%5Cpsi%29%5E2-A%28%5Ctheta%2C%5Cpsi%29%7D%29e%5E%7Bi%5Cpsi%7D%3D%3Ad%2Be%5E%7Bi%5CTheta%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"&#92;displaystyle e^{i&#92;theta}+(B(&#92;theta,&#92;psi)-&#92;sqrt{B(&#92;theta,&#92;psi)^2-A(&#92;theta,&#92;psi)})e^{i&#92;psi}=:d+e^{i&#92;Theta}\" class=\"latex\" /></p><p>where <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5CTheta%3D%5CTheta%28%5Ctheta%2C%5Cpsi%29%5Capprox%5Cpi%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{&#92;Theta=&#92;Theta(&#92;theta,&#92;psi)&#92;approx&#92;pi}\" class=\"latex\" /> and, after a specular reflection, it takes the direction <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Be%5E%7Bi%282%5CTheta-%5Cpsi-%5Cpi%29%7D%3A%3D+e%5E%7Bi%5CPsi%7D%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{e^{i(2&#92;Theta-&#92;psi-&#92;pi)}:= e^{i&#92;Psi}}\" class=\"latex\" />.</p><p>As it is explained in page 35 of Chernov&#8211;Markarian&#8217;s book, this geometric description of the billiard map near the periodic orbit of period two allows to compute <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BDF%5E2%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{DF^2}\" class=\"latex\" /> along the following lines. If we adopt the convention in Chernov&#8211;Markarian&#8217;s book of using arc-length parametrization <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{x}\" class=\"latex\" /> on the obstacle and describing the angle <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7By%5Cin%5B-%5Cpi%2F2%2C%5Cpi%2F2%5D%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{y&#92;in[-&#92;pi/2,&#92;pi/2]}\" class=\"latex\" /> with the normal direction pointing towards the interior of the table using a sign determined by the orientation of the obstacles so that this normal vector stays at the left of the tangent vectors to the obstacles, then the billiard map becomes</p><p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+F%28x%2Cy%29%3A%3D%28X%28x%2Cy%29%2CY%28x%2Cy%29%29%3D%28%5Cpi-%5Carcsin%5Cleft%28%5Csin%28x%29+%2B+t%28x%2C+y%29+%5Csin%28x-y%29%5Cright%29%2C+-X%28x%2Cy%29%2Bx-y%2B%5Cpi%29&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"&#92;displaystyle F(x,y):=(X(x,y),Y(x,y))=(&#92;pi-&#92;arcsin&#92;left(&#92;sin(x) + t(x, y) &#92;sin(x-y)&#92;right), -X(x,y)+x-y+&#92;pi)\" class=\"latex\" /></p><p>where</p><p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+t%28x%2Cy%29%3DB%28x%2Cy%29-%5Csqrt%7BB%28x%2Cy%29%5E2-A%28x%2Cy%29%7D%2C&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"&#92;displaystyle t(x,y)=B(x,y)-&#92;sqrt{B(x,y)^2-A(x,y)},\" class=\"latex\" /></p><p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+B%28x%2Cy%29%3Dd%5Ccos%28x-y%29-%5Ccos%28-y%29%2C+%5Cquad+A%28x%2Cy%29%3Dd%5E2-2d%5Ccos%28x%29%2C&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"&#92;displaystyle B(x,y)=d&#92;cos(x-y)-&#92;cos(-y), &#92;quad A(x,y)=d^2-2d&#92;cos(x),\" class=\"latex\" /></p><p>(and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Carcsin%28z%29%5Cin%5B-%5Cfrac%7B%5Cpi%7D%7B2%7D%2C%5Cfrac%7B%5Cpi%7D%7B2%7D%5D%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{&#92;arcsin(z)&#92;in[-&#92;frac{&#92;pi}{2},&#92;frac{&#92;pi}{2}]}\" class=\"latex\" /> for <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bz%5Cin%5B-1%2C1%5D%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{z&#92;in[-1,1]}\" class=\"latex\" />) and, moreover,</p><p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+D_%7B%28x%2Cy%29%7DF%3D%5Cleft%28%5Cbegin%7Barray%7D%7Bcc%7D+M_%7B11%7D%28x%2Cy%29+%26+M_%7B12%7D%28x%2Cy%29+%5C%5C+M_%7B21%7D%28x%2Cy%29+%26+M_%7B22%7D%28x%2Cy%29%5Cend%7Barray%7D%5Cright%29&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"&#92;displaystyle D_{(x,y)}F=&#92;left(&#92;begin{array}{cc} M_{11}(x,y) & M_{12}(x,y) &#92;&#92; M_{21}(x,y) & M_{22}(x,y)&#92;end{array}&#92;right)\" class=\"latex\" /></p><p>and</p><p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+D_%7B%28X%2CY%29%7DF+%3D+%5Cleft%28%5Cbegin%7Barray%7D%7Bcc%7D+M_%7B11%7D%28%5Cpi-X%28x%2Cy%29%2CY%28x%2Cy%29%29+%26+M_%7B12%7D%28%5Cpi-X%28x%2Cy%29%2CY%28x%2Cy%29%29+%5C%5C+M_%7B21%7D%28%5Cpi-X%28x%2Cy%29%2CY%28x%2Cy%29%29+%26+M_%7B22%7D%28%5Cpi-X%28x%2Cy%29%2CY%28x%2Cy%29%29%5Cend%7Barray%7D%5Cright%29%2C&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"&#92;displaystyle D_{(X,Y)}F = &#92;left(&#92;begin{array}{cc} M_{11}(&#92;pi-X(x,y),Y(x,y)) & M_{12}(&#92;pi-X(x,y),Y(x,y)) &#92;&#92; M_{21}(&#92;pi-X(x,y),Y(x,y)) & M_{22}(&#92;pi-X(x,y),Y(x,y))&#92;end{array}&#92;right),\" class=\"latex\" /></p><p>where</p><p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+%5Cbegin%7Barray%7D%7Brcl%7D+M_%7B11%7D%28x%2Cy%29%26%3D%26-%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B%5Ccos%28Y%28x%2Cy%29%29%7D%28t%28x%2Cy%29%2B%5Ccos%28y%29%29+%5C%5C+%26%3D%26+%281+-+d%29+%2B+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B2%7D+%282+d%5E2+-+d%5E3%29+y%5E2%2B+%28-d+-+d%5E2+%2B+d%5E3%29+xy+%2B+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B2%7D+%28d+-+d%5E3%29+x%5E2+%2B+O%28x%5E3%2Bx%5E2y%5E2%2By%5E3%29%2C+%5Cend%7Barray%7D+&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"&#92;displaystyle &#92;begin{array}{rcl} M_{11}(x,y)&=&-&#92;frac{1}{&#92;cos(Y(x,y))}(t(x,y)+&#92;cos(y)) &#92;&#92; &=& (1 - d) + &#92;frac{1}{2} (2 d^2 - d^3) y^2+ (-d - d^2 + d^3) xy + &#92;frac{1}{2} (d - d^3) x^2 + O(x^3+x^2y^2+y^3), &#92;end{array} \" class=\"latex\" /></p><p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+%5Cbegin%7Barray%7D%7Brcl%7D+M_%7B12%7D%28x%2Cy%29%26%3D%26-%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B%5Ccos%28Y%28x%2Cy%29%29%7Dt%28x%2Cy%29+%5C%5C+%26%3D%26+%282+-+d%29+%2B+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B2%7D+%28-2+d+%2B+3+d%5E2+-+d%5E3%29+y%5E2+%2B+%28-2+d%5E2+%2B+d%5E3%29+xy+%2B+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B2%7D+%28d+%2B+d%5E2+-+d%5E3%29+x%5E2+%2B+O%28x%5E3%2Bx%5E2y%5E2%2By%5E3%29%2C+%5Cend%7Barray%7D+&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"&#92;displaystyle &#92;begin{array}{rcl} M_{12}(x,y)&=&-&#92;frac{1}{&#92;cos(Y(x,y))}t(x,y) &#92;&#92; &=& (2 - d) + &#92;frac{1}{2} (-2 d + 3 d^2 - d^3) y^2 + (-2 d^2 + d^3) xy + &#92;frac{1}{2} (d + d^2 - d^3) x^2 + O(x^3+x^2y^2+y^3), &#92;end{array} \" class=\"latex\" /></p><p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+%5Cbegin%7Barray%7D%7Brcl%7D+M_%7B21%7D%28x%2Cy%29%26%3D%26-%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B%5Ccos%28Y%28x%2Cy%29%29%7D%28t%28x%2C+y%29+%2B+%5Ccos%28Y%28x%2C+y%29%29+%2B+%5Ccos%28y%29%29+%5C%5C+%26%3D%26+-d+%2B+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B2%7D+%282+d%5E2+-+d%5E3%29+y%5E2%2B+%28-d+-+d%5E2%2Bd%5E3%29+xy%2B%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B2%7D+%28d+-+d%5E3%29x%5E2+%2B+O%28x%5E3%2Bx%5E2y%5E2%2By%5E3%29%2C+%5Cend%7Barray%7D+&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"&#92;displaystyle &#92;begin{array}{rcl} M_{21}(x,y)&=&-&#92;frac{1}{&#92;cos(Y(x,y))}(t(x, y) + &#92;cos(Y(x, y)) + &#92;cos(y)) &#92;&#92; &=& -d + &#92;frac{1}{2} (2 d^2 - d^3) y^2+ (-d - d^2+d^3) xy+&#92;frac{1}{2} (d - d^3)x^2 + O(x^3+x^2y^2+y^3), &#92;end{array} \" class=\"latex\" /></p><p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+%5Cbegin%7Barray%7D%7Brcl%7D+M_%7B22%7D%28x%2Cy%29%26%3D%26-%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B%5Ccos%28Y%28x%2Cy%29%29%7D+%28t%28x%2C+y%29+%2B+%5Ccos%28Y%28x%2C+y%29%29%29+%5C%5C+%26%3D%26+%281+-+d%29+%2B+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B2%7D+%28-2+d+%2B+3+d%5E2+-+d%5E3%29+y%5E2+%2B+%28-2+d%5E2+%2B+d%5E3%29+xy+%2B+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B2%7D+%28d+%2B+d%5E2+-+d%5E3%29+x%5E2+%2B+O%28x%5E3%2Bx%5E2y%5E2%2By%5E3%29.+%5Cend%7Barray%7D+&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"&#92;displaystyle &#92;begin{array}{rcl} M_{22}(x,y)&=&-&#92;frac{1}{&#92;cos(Y(x,y))} (t(x, y) + &#92;cos(Y(x, y))) &#92;&#92; &=& (1 - d) + &#92;frac{1}{2} (-2 d + 3 d^2 - d^3) y^2 + (-2 d^2 + d^3) xy + &#92;frac{1}{2} (d + d^2 - d^3) x^2 + O(x^3+x^2y^2+y^3). &#92;end{array} \" class=\"latex\" /></p><p>Since we also have</p><p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+%5Cpi-X%28x%2Cy%29%3D%282+-+d%29+y%2B%28-1+%2B+d%29x%2BO%28%28y%5E2%2Bx%5E2%29%28x%2By%29%29&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"&#92;displaystyle &#92;pi-X(x,y)=(2 - d) y+(-1 + d)x+O((y^2+x^2)(x+y))\" class=\"latex\" /></p><p>and</p><p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+-Y%28x%2Cy%29%3D%28-1+%2B+d%29+y-dx%2BO%28%28y%5E2%2Bx%5E2%29%28x%2By%29%29%2C&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"&#92;displaystyle -Y(x,y)=(-1 + d) y-dx+O((y^2+x^2)(x+y)),\" class=\"latex\" /></p><p>it follows that</p><p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+D_%7B%28x%2Cy%29%7DF%5E2+%3D+%5Cleft%28%5Cbegin%7Barray%7D%7Bcc%7D2d%5E2-4d%2B1+%26+2d%5E2-6d%2B4+%5C%5C+2d%5E2-2d+%26+2d%5E2-4d%2B1%5Cend%7Barray%7D%5Cright%29%2B+Q%28x%2Cy%29%2B+O%28x%5E4%2Bx%5E3y%2By%5E4%2Bx%5E2y%5E2%2Bxy%5E3%29%2C&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"&#92;displaystyle D_{(x,y)}F^2 = &#92;left(&#92;begin{array}{cc}2d^2-4d+1 & 2d^2-6d+4 &#92;&#92; 2d^2-2d & 2d^2-4d+1&#92;end{array}&#92;right)+ Q(x,y)+ O(x^4+x^3y+y^4+x^2y^2+xy^3),\" class=\"latex\" /></p><p>where</p><p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+Q%28x%2Cy%29+%3D+%5Cleft%28%5Cbegin%7Barray%7D%7Bcc%7DQ_%7B11%7D%28x%2Cy%29+%26+Q_%7B12%7D%28x%2Cy%29+%5C%5C+Q_%7B21%7D%28x%2Cy%29+%26+Q_%7B22%7D%28x%2Cy%29%5Cend%7Barray%7D%5Cright%29&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"&#92;displaystyle Q(x,y) = &#92;left(&#92;begin{array}{cc}Q_{11}(x,y) & Q_{12}(x,y) &#92;&#92; Q_{21}(x,y) & Q_{22}(x,y)&#92;end{array}&#92;right)\" class=\"latex\" /></p><p>and</p><p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+%5Cbegin%7Barray%7D%7Brcl%7D+Q_%7B11%7D%28x%2Cy%29%26%3D%26d+%284+-+4+d+-+17+d%5E2+%2B+33+d%5E3+-+20+d%5E4+%2B+4+d%5E5%29+y%5E2+%2B+d+%282+-+4+d+%2B+d%5E2+%2B+9+d%5E3+-+12+d%5E4+%2B+4+d%5E5%29+x%5E2+%5C%5C+%26%2B%26+2+d+%28-3+%2B+5+d+%2B+4+d%5E2+-+19+d%5E3+%2B+16+d%5E4+-+4+d%5E5%29+x+y%2C+%5Cend%7Barray%7D+&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"&#92;displaystyle &#92;begin{array}{rcl} Q_{11}(x,y)&=&d (4 - 4 d - 17 d^2 + 33 d^3 - 20 d^4 + 4 d^5) y^2 + d (2 - 4 d + d^2 + 9 d^3 - 12 d^4 + 4 d^5) x^2 &#92;&#92; &+& 2 d (-3 + 5 d + 4 d^2 - 19 d^3 + 16 d^4 - 4 d^5) x y, &#92;end{array} \" class=\"latex\" /></p><p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+%5Cbegin%7Barray%7D%7Brcl%7D+Q_%7B12%7D%28x%2Cy%29%26%3D%26d+%286+%2B+5+d+-+42+d%5E2+%2B+51+d%5E3+-+24+d%5E4+%2B+4+d%5E5%29+y%5E2+%2B+d+%283+-+5+d+-+4+d%5E2+%2B+19+d%5E3+-+16+d%5E4+%2B+4+d%5E5%29+x%5E2+%5C%5C+%26%2B%26+2+d+%28-4+%2B+4+d+%2B+17+d%5E2+-+33+d%5E3+%2B+20+d%5E4+-+4+d%5E5%29+x+y%2C+%5Cend%7Barray%7D+&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"&#92;displaystyle &#92;begin{array}{rcl} Q_{12}(x,y)&=&d (6 + 5 d - 42 d^2 + 51 d^3 - 24 d^4 + 4 d^5) y^2 + d (3 - 5 d - 4 d^2 + 19 d^3 - 16 d^4 + 4 d^5) x^2 &#92;&#92; &+& 2 d (-4 + 4 d + 17 d^2 - 33 d^3 + 20 d^4 - 4 d^5) x y, &#92;end{array} \" class=\"latex\" /></p><p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+%5Cbegin%7Barray%7D%7Brcl%7D+Q_%7B21%7D%28x%2Cy%29%26%3D%26d+%284+-+6+d+-+16+d%5E2+%2B+33+d%5E3+-+20+d%5E4+%2B+4+d%5E5%29+y%5E2+%2B+d%281+-+2+d%29%5E2+%281+-+2+d%5E2+%2B+d%5E3%29+x%5E2+%5C%5C+%26%2B%26+2+d+%28-2+%2B+6+d+%2B+3+d%5E2+-+19+d%5E3+%2B+16+d%5E4+-+4+d%5E5%29+x+y+%2C+%5Cend%7Barray%7D+&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"&#92;displaystyle &#92;begin{array}{rcl} Q_{21}(x,y)&=&d (4 - 6 d - 16 d^2 + 33 d^3 - 20 d^4 + 4 d^5) y^2 + d(1 - 2 d)^2 (1 - 2 d^2 + d^3) x^2 &#92;&#92; &+& 2 d (-2 + 6 d + 3 d^2 - 19 d^3 + 16 d^4 - 4 d^5) x y , &#92;end{array} \" class=\"latex\" /></p><p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+%5Cbegin%7Barray%7D%7Brcl%7D+Q_%7B22%7D%28x%2Cy%29%26%3D%26d+%288+%2B+2+d+-+41+d%5E2+%2B+51+d%5E3+-+24+d%5E4+%2B+4+d%5E5%29+y%5E2+%2B+d+%282+-+6+d+-+3+d%5E2+%2B+19+d%5E3+-+16+d%5E4+%2B+4+d%5E5%29+x%5E2+%5C%5C+%26%2B%26+2+d+%28-4+%2B+6+d+%2B+16+d%5E2+-+33+d%5E3+%2B+20+d%5E4+-+4+d%5E5%29+x+y.+%5Cend%7Barray%7D+&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"&#92;displaystyle &#92;begin{array}{rcl} Q_{22}(x,y)&=&d (8 + 2 d - 41 d^2 + 51 d^3 - 24 d^4 + 4 d^5) y^2 + d (2 - 6 d - 3 d^2 + 19 d^3 - 16 d^4 + 4 d^5) x^2 &#92;&#92; &+& 2 d (-4 + 6 d + 16 d^2 - 33 d^3 + 20 d^4 - 4 d^5) x y. &#92;end{array} \" class=\"latex\" /></p><p>In particular, the determinant of the quadratic part of the Taylor expansion of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BDF%5E2%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{DF^2}\" class=\"latex\" /> near the periodic orbit of period two <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5C%7Bp_0%2C+p_1%5C%7D%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{&#92;{p_0, p_1&#92;}}\" class=\"latex\" /> is</p><p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+%5Cbegin%7Barray%7D%7Brcl%7D+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7Bd%5E2%7D%5Cdet+Q%28x%2Cy%29+%26%3D%26+%281+-+3+d+-+2+d%5E2+%2B+10+d%5E3+-+8+d%5E4+%2B+2+d%5E5%29+x%5E4+-+2+%28-2+%2B+d%29%5E2+%281+-+d+-+4+d%5E2+%2B+4+d%5E3%29+x%5E3+y+%5C%5C+%26%2B%26+%2822+-+27+d+-+68+d%5E2+%2B+126+d%5E3+-+68+d%5E4+%2B+12+d%5E5%29+x%5E2+y%5E2+-+2+%28-2+%2B+d%29%5E2+%283+%2B+d+-+8+d%5E2+%2B+4+d%5E3%29+x+y%5E3+%5C%5C+%26%2B%26+2+%28-2+%2B+d%29%5E2+%281+-+2+d%5E2+%2B+d%5E3%29+y%5E4+%5Cend%7Barray%7D+&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"&#92;displaystyle &#92;begin{array}{rcl} &#92;frac{1}{d^2}&#92;det Q(x,y) &=& (1 - 3 d - 2 d^2 + 10 d^3 - 8 d^4 + 2 d^5) x^4 - 2 (-2 + d)^2 (1 - d - 4 d^2 + 4 d^3) x^3 y &#92;&#92; &+& (22 - 27 d - 68 d^2 + 126 d^3 - 68 d^4 + 12 d^5) x^2 y^2 - 2 (-2 + d)^2 (3 + d - 8 d^2 + 4 d^3) x y^3 &#92;&#92; &+& 2 (-2 + d)^2 (1 - 2 d^2 + d^3) y^4 &#92;end{array} \" class=\"latex\" /></p><p>Thus, for <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7By%3D-x%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{y=-x}\" class=\"latex\" />, one has</p><p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7Bd%5E2%7D%5Cdet+Q%28x%2C-x%29+%3D+x%5E4+%2863+-+70+d+-+172+d%5E2+%2B+320+d%5E3+-+176+d%5E4+%2B+32+d%5E5%29%2C&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"&#92;displaystyle &#92;frac{1}{d^2}&#92;det Q(x,-x) = x^4 (63 - 70 d - 172 d^2 + 320 d^3 - 176 d^4 + 32 d^5),\" class=\"latex\" /></p><p>so that the quadratic part <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BQ%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{Q}\" class=\"latex\" /> of the Taylor expansion of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BDF%5E2%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{DF^2}\" class=\"latex\" /> is non-degenerate because <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B63+-+70+d+-+172+d%5E2+%2B+320+d%5E3+-+176+d%5E4+%2B+32+d%5E5%5Cgeq+3%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{63 - 70 d - 172 d^2 + 320 d^3 - 176 d^4 + 32 d^5&#92;geq 3}\" class=\"latex\" /> for <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B2%5Cleq+d%5Cleq+4%2F%5Csqrt%7B3%7D%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{2&#92;leq d&#92;leq 4/&#92;sqrt{3}}\" class=\"latex\" />.</p><blockquote><b>Remark 2</b> <em><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cdet+Q%28x%2Cy%29%3D+12+x%5E4%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{&#92;det Q(x,y)= 12 x^4}\" class=\"latex\" /> in the limit case <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bd%3D2%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{d=2}\" class=\"latex\" />.</em></blockquote>",
